  "prompt": "On a train in India, what does SL, 1A, 2A, 3A, 2S, CC mean?",
  "response": "In the Indian Railways system, different classes of travel are denoted by specific abbreviations. Here's what each of those abbreviations stands for:\n\n1. **SL (Sleeper Class)**: This is the most common class and is economical. It consists of non-air-conditioned coaches with sleeping berths, typically used by passengers traveling long distances.\n\n2. **1A (First Class AC)**: This is the most luxurious class, offering air-conditioned coaches with spacious cabins that can be booked either as two-berth or four-berth compartments. It provides high comfort and privacy.\n\n3. **2A (Second Class AC)**: This class provides air-conditioned coaches with sleeping berths arranged in compartments. It is more affordable than First Class AC but still provides good comfort.\n\n4. **3A (Third Class AC)**: This class involves air-conditioned coaches with sleeping berths, but the number of berths in each compartment is higher than in 2A, making it more economical.\n\n5. **2S (Second Seating)**: This class consists of non-air-conditioned coaches with seats (not berths), intended for shorter and daytime journeys. It's one of the most economical classes.\n\n6. **CC (Chair Car)**: This class includes air-conditioned coaches with seats arranged like chairs, intended for shorter journeys typically in day trains like Shatabdi Express. It provides comfort suitable for day travel.\n\nEach class is designed to cater to different levels of comfort and budget constraints for passengers.",
